<h2>The Terms</h2>

<ul>
	<li><strong>Selector:</strong> A way to specify a particular type of tag, e.g. all "a" tags</li>
	<li><strong>Property:</strong> A rule to apply to this tag</li>
	<li><strong>Comment:</strong> Comments are created by starting with a /* and ending with a */</li>
</ul>

<h2>CSS Syntax</h2>

<p>A basic CSS rule might look like:</p>

<div class="annotated-code">
  <pre class="prettyprint linenums lang-css">
/* My Cool Rules */
a
{
	font-weight: bold;
}</pre>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="1">
    An example of a comment
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="2">
    Selects all "a" (link) tags
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="3">
    All the rules must be in between a { and a }
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="4">
    A property such that all tags selected by it will be bold.  (of the form, property-name: property-value; )
  </div>
</div>

<h2>Selectors</h2>

<div class="annotated-code">
  <pre class="prettyprint linenums lang-css">
/* Element selector */
a { }

/* Class selector */
.success { }

/* Id selector */
#search { }

/* Combining selectors */
#search .success { }

a.success { }
</pre>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="2">
    selects all "a" tags
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="5">
    selects all tags with "success" class
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="8">
    selects all tags whose id is "search" (should only be one)
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="11">
    selects all tags with "success" class that are inside a tag with id "search"
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="13">
    no space means select all links that have class "success" (combines them for one element)
  </div>
</div>

<div class="panel panel-info">
  <div class="panel-heading">
    <h3 class="panel-title">Difference between ID and Class</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <p>Many tags can have the same class and therefore is good for describing frequent types of tags, e.g. a blue button.  However, an ID should be unique to the tag, which makes it good if it's the only element in the page, e.g. a search text box.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2>Properties</h2>

<p>Here are some common properties used to style elements:</p>

<div class="annotated-code">
  <pre class="prettyprint linenums lang-css">
a {
	font-weight: bold;
	font-style: italic;
	font-size: 20px;
	color: brown;
}

div {
	border: 1px solid gray;
	background-color: green;
}

body {
	background-image: url('/images/kitten.jpg')
}
</pre>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="2">
    The weight of the font (normal and bold being the most common ones)
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="3">
    The style of the font (normal and italics being the most common ones)
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="4">
    The size of the font in either pixels (e.g. 13px) or em (1.2em), which is relative size to normal sizes.
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="5">
    The color of the text
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="9">
	First value specifies the width of the border, the type of border (solid, dotted), the color of the border
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="10">
	The background color of the div
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="13">
	You can also select body, which will select the entire page
  </div>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="14">
  	You can select a background image, which is useful for repeated backgrounds. (see <a href="http://subtlepatterns.com/">Subtle Patterns</a> for a great resource)
  </div>
</div>

<div class="panel panel-info">
  <div class="panel-heading">
    <h3 class="panel-title">Getting borders on specific sides</h3>
  </div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <p>You can specify a border on only one side by appending "-bottom" (or top, left, right) to the property, e.g. "border-bottom: 1px solid gray".</p>
  </div>
</div>


